  "## 4. Identification Strategy",
  "",
  "### 4.1 Main specification",
  "",
  "The main empirical specification is a difference-in-differences estimator at the tract-month level. Let *y*_{it} denote the log of the median asking rent for a two-bedroom unit in tract *i* in month *t*. The specification is:",
  "",
  "*y*_{it} = α_i + γ_t + β · (Impact_i × Post_t) + **X**_{it}′δ + ε_{it}",
  "",
  "where α_i is a tract fixed effect absorbing time-invariant neighborhood characteristics, γ_t is a calendar-month fixed effect absorbing citywide rental-market shocks, Impact_i is a binary indicator for the eleven tracts within the half-mile ring, and Post_t is an indicator for months from September 2021 onward (the OPC groundbreaking month). The coefficient of interest is β, which we interpret as the log-rent differential between impact zone tracts and comparison tracts in the same two zip codes outside the ring, conditional on month and tract fixed effects.",
  "",
  "The covariate vector **X**_{it} includes time-varying tract characteristics that the literature has identified as potentially confounding: the share of ACS five-year-estimate housing units constructed in the prior decade (to absorb new-construction supply shocks), the share of rental listings in the tract at any given time (to absorb vacancy-rate variation), and an indicator for tract months in which a residential conversion of a non-residential building closed (drawn from Cook County Recorder of Deeds data). We report both the parsimonious specification (without **X**_{it}) and the fully-specified version in §5.3.",
  "",
  "Standard errors are clustered at the tract level, following Abadie et al. (2023) on cluster robust inference in the small-cluster setting. With eleven treated and twelve control tracts, the number of clusters is on the low side of the range for which the asymptotic sandwich estimator is defensible; we therefore report wild-cluster bootstrap *p*-values following Cameron, Gelbach, and Miller (2008) alongside the conventional cluster-robust standard errors.",
  "",
  "### 4.2 The identification assumption",
  "",
  "The parallel-trends assumption underlying the design is that, absent the OPC construction, the impact-zone tracts and the comparison tracts would have followed statistically indistinguishable log-rent trajectories. We test the assumption by examining pre-groundbreaking log-rent differentials. Between January 2020 and August 2021, the twenty months of pre-period data, the impact-zone and control-zone asking rents appreciated at 2.1 percent and 2.4 percent annualized respectively. A Wald test of the difference returns *p* = 0.31, which is not evidence for parallel trends but is at least consistent with them. We also report, as an event-study check, the interaction coefficient on leads of one through twelve months pre-groundbreaking: the leads are statistically indistinguishable from zero (Figure A1 in the appendix).",
  "",
  "Parallel trends is an identifying assumption, not a testable claim; what our tests show is that within the observed pre-period data we cannot reject it. Reasonable readers may nonetheless hold that the Obama Foundation's 2016 announcement initiated an anticipatory effect earlier than 2021, in which case our pre-period is contaminated and β is biased downward. We note this possibility as a limitation in §7 and discuss a sensitivity analysis using an alternative 2016 cutoff in §5.8.",
  "",
  "## 5. Findings",
  "",
  "### 5.1 Descriptive Statistics",
  "",
