  "The monotonic relationship between unit size and appreciation rate, with studios at the top and four-bedroom units at the bottom, is consistent with a demand-composition shift of the kind the anchor-institution theory predicts. The marginal renter attracted by a new institutional amenity is, in the typical case, a single adult or a childless couple with a relatively high willingness-to-pay for proximity and a relatively low demand for bedroom count. Family-sized units, where the elasticity runs primarily through the quality of nearby schools rather than through proximity to employment amenities, show smaller appreciation.",
