  "",
  "Tracts at the southern edge of the ring (Greater Grand Crossing and the northern edge of South Shore) show smaller premia, on the order of 30 to 34 percent, from higher baselines. The pattern is a textbook illustration of distance decay (Rosenthal & Ross 2015; Guerrieri et al. 2013): the local premium attenuates with distance from the investment's activity center, and the attenuation is partly offset by baseline differences that themselves correlate with distance. The implication for policy design, which we take up in §8, is that blanket ring-wide instruments are likely to over-protect the highest-baseline tracts and under-protect the tracts bearing the largest marginal pressure.",
  "",
  "### 5.6 Robustness",
  "",
